    <h2>Section A: Attempt any two questions.</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain strong induction in detail. What is recursively defined function? Use mathematical induction to prove 7<sup>n+2</sup> + 8<sup>2</sup><sup>n+1</sup>  is divisible by 5</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Strong induction</strong> is a type of proof closely related to simple induction.</p>
<p>As in simple induction, we have a statement P(n) about the whole number n, and we want to prove that P(n) is true for every value of n. To prove this using strong induction, we do the following:</p>
<p><strong>The base case:</strong></p>
<p>We prove that P(1) is true (or occasionally P(0) or some other P(n) , depending on the problem).</p>
<p><strong>The induction step:</strong></p>
<p>We prove that if P(1) , P(2) , …, P(k) are all true, then P(k+1) must also be true. In this step, the assumption that P(1) , …, P(k) are true is called the inductive hypothesis. Together, these imply that P(n) is true for all whole numbers n . (The proof is the same as with simple induction.) The critical difference between this and simple induction is that in step 2, we do not assume that only P(k) is true, but P(k) and all earlier P(i) for i&lt;k.</p>
<p>It is convenient if the proof of P(k+1) might depend on not only the previous P(k) but on any earlier P(i). It turns out that this form of induction is actually equivalent to simple induction: anything one can prove with one of them, one can also prove with the other.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Recursively defined function</strong> is a function that repeats or uses its own previous term to calculate subsequent terms and thus forms a sequence of terms.</p>
<p>Example: For a fibonacci series, recursively defined function is as:</p>
<p>F<sub>n</sub> = F<sub>n-1</sub> + F<sub>n-2</sub> for n&gt;1 and</p>
<p>F<sub>n</sub> = n for n=0,1.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Proof by mathematical induction:</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>To prove:</p>
<p>P(n): 7<sup>n+2</sup> + 8<sup>2</sup><sup>n+1</sup>  is divisible by 57 for every nonnegative integer n.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Base case:</strong></p>
<p>for n=0,</p>
<p>P(0) = 7<sup>0+2</sup> + 8<sup>2*0+1</sup> = 57 = divisible by 57.</p>
<p>Hence P(0) is true for n=0.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Inductive case:</strong></p>
<p>Let us assume P(k) is true where k∈n i.e.</p>
<p>P(k): 7<sup>k+2</sup> + 8<sup>2k</sup><sup>+1</sup>  is divisible by 57 ; k∈n</p>
<p>i.e 7<sup>k+2</sup> + 8<sup>2k</sup><sup>+1</sup> = 57*a ; a=integer value.</p>
<p>Now, under this assumption, we show that P(k+1) is true i.e.</p>
<p>To prove:</p>
<p>P(k+1): 7<sup>(k+1)+2</sup> + 8<sup>2(k</sup><sup>+1)+1</sup>  is divisible by 57 ; k∈n</p>
<p>We have:</p>
<p>P(k+1) = 7<sup>(k+1)+2</sup> + 8<sup>2(k</sup><sup>+1)+1</sup></p>
<p>= 7<sup>k+2+1</sup> + 8<sup>2k</sup><sup>+1+2</sup></p>
<p>=7<sup>k+2</sup> .  7 + 8<sup>2k</sup><sup>+1</sup> . 64</p>
<p>=(57a &#8211; 8<sup>2k</sup><sup>+1</sup>) .  7 + 8<sup>2k</sup><sup>+1</sup> . 64 [from inductive hypothesis]</p>
<p>= 57 * 7a + 8<sup>2k</sup><sup>+1 </sup>(64 &#8211; 7)</p>
<p>= 57 * 7a + 8<sup>2k</sup><sup>+1</sup> * 57</p>
<p>= 57 ( 7a + 8<sup>2k</sup><sup>+1</sup>)</p>
<p>= divisible by 57.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Therefore, P(k+1) is true whenever P(k) is true.</p>
<p>Hence, P(n) is true i.e.</p>
<p>7<sup>n+2</sup> + 8<sup>2</sup><sup>n+1</sup>  is divisible by 57 for every nonnegative integer n.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>State pigeonhole principle. Solve the recurrence relation a<sub>n</sub> = 5a<sub>n-1</sub> – 6a<sub>n-2</sub> with initial conditions a<sub>0</sub> = 1 and a<sub>1</sub> = 3.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Pigeonhole Principle</strong></p>
<p>If k+1 or more pigeons are placed into k pigeonholes then there is at least one pigeonhole containing two or more pigeons.</p>
