<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>Express the following sentences using quantifier.</p>
<p>a. Not all people are loyal.</p>
<p>b. Everybody loves somebody.</p>
<p>c. Someone has passed the exam.</p>
<p>d. Aquatic animals can’t live without water.</p>
<p>e. Some subjects are not interesting.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>a. Not all people are loyal.</strong></p>
<p>=&gt;</p>
<p>People(x): x is a person.</p>
<p>Loyal(x): x is loyal.</p>
<p>∃x People(x) ∧ ¬Loyal(x)</p>
<p><strong>b. Everybody loves somebody.</strong></p>
<p>=&gt; ∀x ∃y Loves(x,y)</p>
<p><strong>c. Someone has passed the exam.</strong></p>
<p>=&gt;</p>
<p>Exam(x): x has given the exam.</p>
<p>Passed(x): x has passed the exam.</p>
<p>∃x Exam(x) ∧ Passed(x)</p>
<p><strong>d. Aquatic animals can&#8217;t live without water.</strong></p>
<p>=&gt;</p>
<p>Animal(x): x is an animal.</p>
<p>Aquatic(x): x is aquatic.</p>
<p>Live(x): x can live without water.</p>
<p>∀x ( Animal(x) ∧ Aquatic(x) ) → ¬Live(x)</p>
<p><strong>e. Some subjects are not interesting.</strong></p>
<p>=&gt;</p>
<p>Subject(x): x is a subject.</p>
<p>Interesting(x): x is interesting.</p>
<p>∃x Subject(x) ∧ ¬Interesting(x)</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>What is proof by contradiction? Give a proof by contradiction to show that if 3n+2 is odd then n is odd.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Proof by contradiction</strong></p>
<p>We use negation of statement to be true.</p>
<p>Using rules and facts, we reach to contradiction.</p>
<p>Then, we conclude that our assumption is false and statement is true.</p>
<p>In case of implication, we assume hypothesis to be true and conclusion to be false.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>To prove: If 3n+2 is odd, then n is odd.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Proof:</strong></p>
<p>We assume 3n+2 is odd and n is even.</p>
<p>then,</p>
<p>if n is even, n=2k ; k is any integer.</p>
<p>3n + 2 = 3*2k + 2 = 6k + 2 = 2(3k+1) = even</p>
<p>This means 3n + 2 is even i.e. our assumption is false and the given statement is false.</p>
<p>i.e. If 3n+2 is odd, n is odd.</p>
<p><strong>PROVED!!!</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>State the necessary conditions for two graphs to be isomorphic. How many different words from “MANAGER” can be generated with or without meaning?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>If two graphs are isomorphic, they must have:<br />
&#8211; the same number of vertices<br />
&#8211; the same number of edges<br />
&#8211; the same degrees for corresponding vertices<br />
&#8211; the same number of connected components<br />
&#8211; the same number of loops<br />
&#8211; the same number of parallel edges.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The word &#8220;MANAGER&#8221; can be arranged in (7! / 2!) i.e. 2520 ways</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Define symmetric closure. What is the symmetric closure of the relation R = {(1,1), (1,2), (2,2), (2,3), (3,1), (3,2)} on the set A = {1,2,3}?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>In set theory, the symmetric closure of a binary relation R on a set A is a new binary relation that contains all pairs (a, b) for which (b, a) is already in R. In other words, if (a, b) is in R, then (b, a) is also added to the symmetric closure of R. The symmetric closure makes the relation symmetric, meaning it works in both directions.</p>
<p>Mathematically, if R is a binary relation on A, then the symmetric closure of R, denoted as R<sup>s</sup>, is defined as:</p>
<p>R<sup>s</sup> = R ∪ {(b, a) | (a, b) ∈ R}</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Given:</p>
<p>R={(1,1) , (1,2) , (2,2) , (2,3) , (3,1) , (3,2)}</p>
<p>then,</p>
<p>R<sup>s </sup>= {(1,1) , (1,2) , (1,3) , (2,1) , (2,2) , (2,3) , (3,1) , (3,2) }</p>
</div>
